3-NETWORK LOGS

10.3.1 tcpdump
Command-line packet capture tool for recording and analyzing network traffic.
Captures complete packets, including headers and payloads.
Forms the basis for graphical tools like Wireshark.
10.3.2 NetFlow
Records metadata about network flows instead of full packet contents.
Tracks source/destination IPs, ports, protocols, timestamps, and byte counts.
Supports network monitoring, troubleshooting, and security investigations.
IPFIX is the standardized version based on Cisco NetFlow.
10.3.3 Application Visibility and Control (AVC)
Identifies and classifies applications using NBAR2.
Provides visibility into application usage beyond traditional port-based monitoring.
Enables traffic prioritization, bandwidth management, and policy enforcement.
10.3.4 Content Filter Logs
ESA (Email Security Appliance) logs spam, malware, antivirus, and email filtering events.
WSA (Web Security Appliance) logs web requests, malware detections, URL filtering, and ACL decisions.
Supports centralized security monitoring and incident analysis.
10.3.5 Cisco Device Logging
Cisco devices generate Syslog messages containing timestamps, severity levels, facilities, and event descriptions.
Used for centralized monitoring and troubleshooting of network infrastructure.
10.3.6 Proxy Logs
Proxy servers log web and DNS requests made by users.
Useful for monitoring browsing activity, detecting malicious destinations, and preventing data loss.
Cisco Umbrella enhances DNS security using cloud-based threat intelligence.
10.3.7 Next-Generation Firewalls (NGFW)
NGFWs provide advanced security features including application awareness, IPS, malware protection, URL filtering, and VPN support.
Common event types:
Connection Event – Records network sessions.
Intrusion Event – Detects malicious activity.
Host/Endpoint Event – Logs newly detected devices.
Network Discovery Event – Detects changes in the network.
NetFlow Event – Generated from NetFlow-based network discovery.

